Violence a Destruction  He was sitting on the grass with a tea in his left hand speaking to her at the protest site. He looked at the sunrise, and she at the tea in her hand. They spoke about the peaceful protest that had been held for the 31st day straight. Their intentions were peaceful, as many millions of protestors had attended with their families over the past weeks. It was their 21st day straight at the protest site. Proud of themselves and the progress made. They knew it was never going to be easy.   Their intentions and actions have been continuously peaceful. The activities at the protest site have not only been peaceful, but very innovative and colorful. _A colorful revolution. She said that their generation was on the verge of transforming the entire country. They had achieved unimaginable progress towards transforming their future. Not only their future but the future of the past, present and future generations. He said the peaceful protest was unprecedented. They spoke about Ghandi, Martin Luther King and even Nelsen Mandela. They expected a positive outcome that day. This was a massive victory. A victory achieved through non-violence. A great achievement for innocent people.   Now she sits at the same location in the dark physically beaten by mobs. Whilst he is at hospital assaulted. She thinks of him. She does not know how well he is doing. Whether he is ok? Whether he is thinking of her? Whether he knows she is ok? She wants quick news. But there is no communication. Her tears continue to fall. Tears of sorrow mixed with courage to continue the fight through non – violent means stronger than before. She knows that they will win. She knows her courage is far greater than the goons and thugs.   The cronies and thugs used violence in an unprecedented manner. They took the law to their hands. Abused the innocent non-violent protestors. Although, they were brutally assaulted; determination, righteousness, humility, patience, long suffering and non-violence has been the cornerstone of their struggle for a future that can be rejoiced and celebrated.   Today, she thought that we are marching towards our goal. Success will come their way. The peaceful struggle will continue.   She looked to the dark sky. She received a message from him. “hope you will get this message, How are you? I am ok” he wrote.     We at CBH Land condemn the use of violence in this non-violent, peaceful and humble movement on innocent protestors.

#no_default_fears   Sri Lanka's External Debt Dynamic:   Sri Lanka is approx  USD 90 billion economy. The economy will generate Forex Inflows of approximately USD 32 billion in 2021, and possibly about USD 3 to 4 billion more than that amount, each year, every year, thereafter.   As of now (February 2021), the total ISBs outstanding is USD 14 billion, which is only 16.7% of Sri Lanka's total debt. None of the other Creditors who hold 83.3% of Sri Lanka's Debt seem to show any sign of concern or stress about it's repayment ability except foreign banks and some doomsday commentators.   Sri Lanka has to re-pay only around USD 1.0 to 1.5 billion each year until 2029 in it's ISB amortizations for the next 8 years.   In that background, will the authorities be so foolish as to default on a payment of around USD 1.0 to 1.5 billion per annum and risk it's entire economy and impeccable credit history?  #Sri_Lanka_Can

UK mortgage borrowers are more vulnerable to inflation and rising interest rates than those in other European nations.  That’s according to research by Moody’s Investors Service Ltd, which says almost 13% of British borrowers could face financial distress if the UK sees high-single-digit inflation next year, alongside an aggressive rise in interest rates.   In contrast, the impact of rising rates on European nations such as Spain, Italy and France will be softer given their high share of long-term, fixed-rate loans. In these nations, a large share of floating interest rate loans have been gradually written off, having originated from periods of historically high interest.  Since then, mortgage borrowers in Spain and Italy have largely moved away from floating loans due to low interest rates, helping to shield portfolios from rising costs. In the UK, the spectrum of borrowers is broader, meaning they are more vulnerable to inflationary pressures.  Residential mortgages are in the firing line from inflation and interest rates because rate hikes used to combat surging prices increase borrowers’ costs. Inflation is likely to peak in 2022, but commodity price shocks driven by Russia’s invasion of Ukraine could amplify pressures and uncertainty, Moody’s said.
